[[File:Bahey El Din Barakat Pasha.JPG|thumb|right|Bahey El Din Barakat Pasha]]
'''Bahey El Din Barakat Pasha''' ({{Lang-ar|بهي الدين بركات باشا
}}) (1889–1972) was an Egyptian political figure.

Born in Menyat El Morshed village (in [[Kafr el-Sheikh Governorate]]), he studied in [[Cairo]] as well as in [[Paris]]. Originally a law teacher, he entered politics and was appointed [[Ministry of Education (Egypt)|Minister of Education]] twice during the 1930s.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Hassan |first=Karima |date=24 August 2007|script-title=ar:عشرات الوزراء للتعليم في مصر خلال ٨٢ سنة فقط |trans-title=Dozens of ministers of education in Egypt in the span of 82 years only |journal=[[Almasry Alyoum]] |url=http://modernegypt.bibalex.org/DocumentViewer/TextViewer.aspx?w=1344&h=646&type=press&id=1883&s=1 |language=Arabic |format=Reprint |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref> During his tenure, a committee was established to facilitate [[Arabic grammar]] rules in order to make it easier for students to study in Arabic. He paid attention to the improvement of [[textbook]]s, and created an admission system for the High Institute of Education in 1938. In January of the same year, he inaugurated [[List of FM radio stations in Egypt|Egypt's radio broadcasting]] service.<ref>{{cite web | title = Ministers of Education from the Kafr el-Sheikh Governorate | language = Arabic | publisher = Official website of the Kafr el-Sheikh Governorate | url = http://www.kafrelshiekh.gov.eg/p2.htm | accessdate = 2008-08-02 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080517162405/http://www.kafrelshiekh.gov.eg/p2.htm | archivedate = 2008-05-17}}</ref>

A leading figure of the [[Wafd Party]] during [[Saad Zaghlul]]'s leadership as well as during the reign of King [[Farouk of Egypt|Farouk I]], Bahey El Din Barakat was elected [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker]] of the [[Parliament of Egypt|Chamber of Deputies]] on 12 April 1938, a position he held for a year and a half.<ref>{{cite web|title=Previous Presidents |publisher=Official website of the Egyptian People's Assembly |url=http://www.parliament.gov.eg/English/AboutTheParlmanet/Xpresidents/farok.htm |accessdate=2008-08-02 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

Barakat received the nobiliary title of ''[[Pasha]]'' on 15 February 1938.<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Pashas (1915-52) |url=http://www.egy.com/historica/pashalst.htm |accessdate=2008-08-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080628164903/http://www.egy.com/historica/pashalst.htm |archivedate=2008-06-28 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> He headed the [[Central Auditing Organization|Divan of Accounting]] from 1945 to 1949.<ref>{{cite web|title=Previous Chairmen |publisher=Official website of the Central Auditing Organization |url=http://www.cao.gov.eg/english/dpages_dpagesdetails.asp?ID=31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040624085349/http://www.cao.gov.eg/english/DPages_DPagesDetails.asp?ID=31 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2004-06-24 |accessdate=2008-08-03 }}</ref> He also served on the three-member [[Regencies in Egypt|Regency Body]] that was formed following the [[Egyptian Revolution of 1952|1952 Revolution]] to assume the powers of King [[Fuad II of Egypt|Fuad II]], who was barely six months old at the time. The Regency Body had no actual powers, however, these having been effectively assumed by the [[Egyptian Revolutionary Command Council|Revolutionary Command Council]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Rizk | first = Yunan Labib | title = Royal help | journal = [[Al-Ahram Weekly]] | issue = 727 | date = 27 January – 2 February 2005 | url = http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2005/727/chrncls.htm | issn = 1110-2977 | oclc = 163624446 | accessdate = 2008-07-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080906143901/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2005/727/chrncls.htm| archivedate= 6 September 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Created on 2 August 1952, the Regency Body was dissolved on 14 October of the same year, with [[Prince Muhammad Abdel Moneim]] being appointed as sole [[regent]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Facts on File Yearbook |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uo4YAAAAIAAJ&q=Prince+Moneim |accessdate=2010-08-08 |volume=Volume 12 |year=1953 |publisher=Facts on File |page=327}}</ref>

