{{BLP sources|date=December 2017}} {{EngvarB|date=October 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Michael Shadlen | birth_name =Michael Neil Shadlen | image = MIchaelShadlen.png | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1959|08|19}} | birth_place = New York City, New York | death_date = | death_place = | residence = [[New York City]] | citizenship = [[United States]] | nationality = | thesis_title = Neural Mechanisms of Stereoscopic Depth Perception | thesis_year = 1985 | thesis_url = | ethnicity = | fields = {{Plainlist| * [[Neuroscience]]}} | workplaces = {{Plainlist| * [[Columbia University]] * [[University of Washington]]}} | alma_mater ={{Plainlist| * [[Brown University]] (BA) * [[University of California, Berkeley]] (PhD) * [[Brown University]] (MD)}} | doctoral_advisor = Ralph D Freeman | academic_advisors = [[William Newsome]] | doctoral_students = | known_for = | awards = {{Plainlist| * [[Golden Brain Award]] (2012)}} | religion = | signature = | footnotes = | spouse = Helen Brew | website = {{URL|www.shadlenlab.columbia.edu}} }}
'''Michael Neil Shadlen''' (born 19 August 1959) is an American [[neuroscientist]] and [[neurologist]], who has made contributions in the [[neuroscience]] of decision making.<ref name="googlescholar">{{GoogleScholar|Q0kenzsAAAAJ}}</ref> From 2000 he has been a [[HHMI|Howard Hughes Medical Investigator]] and from 2012 Professor of Neuroscience at [[Columbia University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=HHMI investigator|url=http://www.hhmi.org/scientists/michael-n-shadlen|website=HHMI.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shadlen Lab at Columbia University|url=https://www.shadlenlab.columbia.edu/|website=www.shadlenlab.columbia.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CV|url=https://www.shadlenlab.columbia.edu/people/mike/MShadlen_CV.pdf}}</ref> He is also a member of the Kavli Institute for Brain Science and Mortimer B. Zuckerman Mind Brain Behavior Institute. Shadlen is a jazz guitarist and interested in the relation between jazz and neuroscience.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Neurons Tell Time|url=https://soundcloud.com/carrytheoneradio/14-how-neurons-tell-time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Columbia’s Zuckerman Institute Presents Jazz in the Brain: A Dialogue of Sound and Science|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qpq7okDgbzs}}</ref>
==Education== Shadlen completed his B.A at [[Brown University]] in 1981 and a PhD at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1985. He completed an MD at [[Brown University]] in 1988.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
==Career== Shadlen did residency training at Stanford Medical School where he was Chief Resident 1991-1992 and Clinical Instructor 1993-94. He pursued neuroscience as a [[postdoctoral research]]er (1993–1995) at [[Stanford University School of Medicine|Stanford Medical School]] before joining the faculty of the Department of Physiology and Biophysics, [[University of Washington]] where he became a [[HHMI|Howard Hughes Medical Investigator]] in 2000. He practised neurology as an Adjunct Assistant, Associate and Full Professor of Neurology at University of Washington (1995-2012).{{cn|date=December 2017}}
==Awards and honours== Shadlen was elected a Member of the [[National Academy of Medicine]] in 2014 and a Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine|url=http://www8.nationalacademies.org/onpinews/newsitem.aspx?RecordID=10202014A|website=www8.nationalacademies.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2015 AAAS Fellows Recognized for Contributions to Advancing Science|url=https://www.aaas.org/news/2015-aaas-fellows-recognized-contributions-advancing-science|date=16 November 2015}}</ref>
Other awards include: * 1995-1997 McKnight Scholar Award *2007 Swartz foundation Mind-Brain Lecture, [[Stony Brook University]] *2009 [[W. Alden Spencer Award|Alden Spencer Prize]], [[Columbia University]] *2012 [[Golden Brain Award]] of the [[Minerva Foundation]] *2014 Fellow of Association for Psychological Science *2017 Karl Spencer Lashley Award, American Philosophical Society
