{{refimprove|date=September 2016}} {{EngvarB|date=February 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}} The '''Sijil Pelajaran Malaysia''' ('''SPM'''), or the '''Malaysian Certificate of Education''', is a national examination taken by all [[Education in Malaysia#Secondary education|fifth-form]] secondary school students in [[Malaysia]]. It is the equivalent to the [[General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (GCSE) in England, Wales and Northern Ireland; [[Scottish Qualifications Authority#Qualification types|Nationals 4/5]] in Scotland; and [[GCE Ordinary Level]] in the [[Commonwealth of Nations]]. It is the leaving examination of the [[eleventh grade]] of schooling.
SPM is the penultimate examination sat by secondary school students before entry into [[sixth form]] or [[vocational education|technical education]]. The examination is set and examined by the Malaysian Examinations Syndicate (''Lembaga Peperiksaan Malaysia'').
==History== The SPM is equivalent to the British [[GCSE]], and provides the opportunity for Malaysians to continue their studies to pre-university level. Up to 1978, the examination was handled by [[UCLES]], which still advises the Malaysian Examinations Syndicate on standards. The English paper is separately graded by the national examination board and [[UCLES]], and both grades will be displayed on the statement slip. On the actual certificate, only the national examination board's grade is listed. The minimum requirements to obtain the certificate is to pass both Malay language and History.
Generally, the SPM is taken at the age of 17, though students who attended pre-secondary school class would take it at the age of 18. Previously, students who successfully passed their [[Education in Malaysia#Primary|Penilaian Tahap Satu]] (PTS) examination at Primary Three and chose to skip a year of primary school education would take their SPM a year earlier, at the age of 16. This was discontinued in 2000. Students who are [[homeschooling|home schooled]] generally take the SPM at the end of their secondary education as well.
==Subjects==
===Compulsory subjects=== Certain subjects are made compulsory for students. These are:<ref>{{cite web |publisher=MyExam.com |url=http://iphira.tripod.com/smih/spm.htm |title=Apa itu SPM? |accessdate=22 November 2011}} {{ms icon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |publisher=Ministry of Education, Malaysia |url=http://www.moe.gov.my/?id=48 |title=Secondary School Subjects |accessdate=22 November 2011}} {{ms icon}}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" width="100%" |- !width="10%"|Code !width="35%"|Subject (Official name) !width="35%"|Subject (English name) !width="20%"|Examination language |- | style="text-align:center;" | 1103 | [[Malay language|Bahasa Melayu]] | Malay Language | Malay |- | style="text-align:center;" | 1119 | [[English language|Bahasa Inggeris]] | English Language | English |- | style="text-align:center;" | 1223 | [[Islamic studies|Pendidikan Islam]]{{ref label|islam|a|a}} | Islamic Studies | Malay |- | style="text-align:center;" | 1225 | [[Pendidikan Moral]]{{ref label|moral|b|b}} | Moral Studies | Malay |- | style="text-align:center;" | 1249 | [[History|Sejarah]] | History | Malay |- | style="text-align:center;" | 1449 | [[Mathematics]] | Mathematics | English and Malay |- | style="text-align:center;" | 1511 | [[Science]]{{ref label|science|c|c}} | Science | English and Malay |}
{| |- | {{note label|islam|a|a}} Compulsory for all [[Muslim]] students except for students in Islamic Science stream, who are required to take their respective electives in lieu of this subject. |- | {{note label|moral|b|b}} Compulsory for all non-Muslim students. |- | {{note label|science|c|c}} Compulsory for students in the Commerce, and Literature and Arts streams only. Students in the Pure Science, Islamic Science, and Humanities Science streams are required to take their respective Science electives in lieu of this subject (see below). |}
===Elective subjects===
